      <hedline>
        <hl1>Future Justice</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rita R Brownback letter, commenting on Bob Herbert's May 25 column, expresses anxiety over women's right to abortion if a Republican president should have opportunity to replace one or more Supreme Court justices</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bob Herbert's excellent summation of potential right-wing accomplishments should a Republican president have the opportunity to replace one or more Supreme Court justices with new ones (column, May 25) brought two thoughts to mind.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Bob Herbert's excellent summation of potential right-wing accomplishments should a Republican president have the opportunity to replace one or more Supreme Court justices with new ones (column, May 25) brought two thoughts to mind.</p>
        <p>If Roe v. Wade, the 1973 decision legalizing abortion, is overturned, abortion may become illegal but would still be readily available to anyone with sufficient funds, just as any cognizant adult could observe was the case in the years before 1973. And second, the male justices and legislators who long to make pregnancy enforceable, no matter the circumstances, are requiring a hardship for women that they themselves will never experience.</p>
        <p>RITA R. BROWNBACK  Eagles Mere, Pa., May 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
